Exercise 3 : Modeling.

1. Given the results derived from the previous sections, propose the most relevant ARMA(p,q) framework to model the retail sales dynamics. Is there an alternative to the ARMA(p,d) approach ?

Pour pouvoir appliquer un modle ARMA, il faut une srie dsaisonnalise et stationnaire. On a dj retirer les pics de saisonnalit dans la premire partie. Dans la seconde partie, on a montrer travers trois tests statistiques quil lordre dintgration de la srie temporelle Retail Sales est d = 1. De ce fait, on commence par appliquer un test en diffrence premire pour obtenir une srie stationnaire.

library(ggplot2)
stationnary_TS <- diff(ts.sa)
plot(stationnary_TS)

acf(stationnary_TS, lag = 120)

On observe alors que lallure srie obtenue est stationnaire et que les rsidus sont faiblement autocorrls, on peut alors commencer chercher le modle arma le plus pertinent.

On commence par reprsenter lacf et la Pacf pour obtenir une approximation dordre MA et de lordre AR.

acf(stationnary_TS, lag = 6)

pacf(stationnary_TS, lag = 10)

On observe dans un premier temps une premiere estimation : un modle qui approche les donnes serait un ARMA(2,3) (on considre les pics qui dpassent significativement la limite statistique tablie).

AR_order <- seq(0,4)
MA_order <- seq(0,4)


likelihood = matrix(0,nrow = max(AR_order),ncol = max(MA_order))
AIC = matrix(0,nrow = max(AR_order),ncol = max(MA_order))
BIC = matrix(0,nrow = max(AR_order),ncol = max(MA_order))

for (p in AR_order) {
  for (q in MA_order) {
    model = arima(stationnary_TS, order = c(p,0,q))
    likelihood[p,q] = model$loglik # On recup la log vraissemblance
    AIC[p,q] = model$aic # On recupre l'AIC
    BIC[p,q] = BIC(model) # On recupre le BIC
  }
}

auto_arma43 <- arima(stationnary_TS, order = c(4,0,4))
residus <- auto_arma43$residuals
estimated <-(stationnary_TS - residus)
plot(stationnary_TS, col = "red")
lines(estimated, col = "green")

On observe alors que lapproximation est plutt bonne mais non optimale.

On considre le modle ARIMA, extension du modle ARMA. On a determin que le degr dintgration optimal est d = 1.

auto_arma44 <- arima(ts.sa, order = c(4,1,4))
residus2 <- auto_arma44$residuals
estimated <- (ts.sa - residus)
plot(ts.sa, col = "black")
lines(estimated, col = "red")

le modle ARIMA tant efficace sur les sris non stationnaires. On obtient un rsultat pertinent. la modlisation est trs proche des observations.

2. Determine the order of the ARIMA model, i.e the values of p, d, q to be used to model the stock prices. Note first, the assessment of p and q cannot be performed on the data expressed in level.Note besides, the determination of the values of p and q can be performed using different methods (graphical approach vs information criteria).

stationnary_prices <- diff(stock_prices)

armaloop=function(ts){
  aics=0
  k=1
  for (p in 0:4){
    for (q in 0:4){
      arma=arima(ts,order=c(p,0,q)) 
      aics[k]=AIC(arma)
      k=k+1
    }
  }
  names(aics)=c("(0,0)","(0,1)","(0,2)","(0,3)","(0,4)","(1,0)","(1,1)","(1,2)","(1,3)","(1,4)","(2,0)","(2,1)","(2,2)","(2,3)","(2,4)","(3,0)","(3,1)","(3,2)","(3,3)","(3,4)","(4,0)","(4,1)","(4,2)","(4,3)","(4,4)")
  return(aics)
}
armaloop(stationnary_prices)

Exercise 5 : Unit root test another one :

1. Present the Zivot and Andrews (1992) test paying attention to the nature of the breaks. Explain the strategy of the test.

Ce test analyse si le modle une racine unitaire et des breaks Hypothse H0: la srie une racine unitaire avec break(s) Hypothse H1: la srie est stationaire avec break(s) On rejette lhypothse nulle si la t-statistic est < la critical value

2. Generate 3 new random walks. The first one is a pure random walk, the second is a random walk with a break in level and the third on will be a random walk with both a break in level and in the trend.

par(mfrow = c(3,1))
#Simulation of a withe noise process
set.seed(123)
w.n = rnorm(1000,0,1.7)

#generate simple a random walk 
rw = cumsum(w.n)
plot(rw,type="l", main = "Simple random walk")


shock = function(taille)
{
  norm=0
  set.seed(4)
  al=sample(1:1000,1)
  print(al)
  for(i in 2:1000){
    if(i==al){
      norm[i]=rnorm(1,0,taille)
    }
    else{
      norm[i]=norm[i-1]
    }
  }
  return(norm)
}

#gnration d'un random walk avec break
rw.break.level = rw +shock(80)
## [1] 504
plot(rw.break.level,type="l", col = "blue", main ="Random walk with break in level")

#gnration d'une tendance t et d'un random walk simple avec drift et shock
t = 1:1000
rw.break.trend = rw + 0.15*t +shock(80)
## [1] 504
plot(rw.break.trend ,type="l", col = "red", main = "Random walk with break in trend ")

residus2 <- arima_d2$residuals
